SIMPLE: incubus
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incubus
<hw>In"cu*bus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E.
<plw>Incubuses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Incubi</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., the nightmare. Cf.
<er>Incubate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A demon; a fiend; a lascivious spirit, supposed to
have sexual intercourse with women by night.</def>
<rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The devils who appeared in the female form were generally called
succubi; those who appeared like men <qex>incubi</qex>, though this
distinction was not always preserved.</q> <rj><qau>Lecky.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The nightmare. See
<er>Nightmare</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such as are troubled with <qex>incubus</qex>, or witch-ridden, as
we call it.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any oppressive encumbrance or burden; anything that
prevents the free use of the faculties.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Debt and usury is the <qex>incubus</qex> which weighs most heavily
on the agricultural resources of Turkey.</q> <rj><qau>J. L.
Farley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inculcate</ent>⟦br⟧
